This paper presents a comprehensive safety framework based on hyperpleonastic redundancy for the Caldera Reactor—a next-generation system operating under extreme environmental conditions. By integrating multiple layers of physical, thermal, cybernetic, and bio-inspired safeguards, our design achieves unprecedented fault tolerance and resilience. In particular, we detail ten interdependent protective layers, each equipped with advanced mathematical models—from second-order damping dynamics to Bayesian hazard inference—and real-time adaptive control strategies. Our approach demonstrates how the synthesis of passive and active controls can maintain system integrity even in the face of severe disturbances.
