Modern reactor systems operate under highly dynamic and often hostile conditions. To ensure both operational safety and reliability, traditional designs have incorporated multiple layers of redundancy. Building on this concept, we introduce a hyperpleonastic design strategy that combines physical damping, thermal buffering, real-time simulation via digital twins, adaptive control interfaces, environmental monitoring, redundant actuation, bio-feedback integration, cyber-physical security, energy management, and an ultimate cryogenic isolation barrier.

